            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being fourteen in his dad's garage, the smell of motor oil and burnt solder mixing in the Daly City fog. His dad was under a car, but watched as Leo methodically disassembled a broken VCR. When Leo finally found the snapped belt and cheered, his father grunted his approval. It wasn't praise, but acknowledgment. In that moment, Leo understood his hands were his tools, and fixing things was a language they both spoke, even if his vocabulary was circuits instead of carburetors.\n\n2.\nThe satellite feed for the 10 o'clock news was gone, and Frank, the gruff chief engineer, was cursing. Leo, then just 22 and fetching coffee, quietly pointed to a blinking red light on a patch panel everyone had ignored. A quick switch, and the feed roared back to life with seconds to spare. Frank didn't say much, just a gruff, \"Huh. Good eye, kid.\" That nod of respect from the old master felt more valuable than any diploma, cementing his place behind the scenes.\n\n3.\nThe Warriors won the championship, and the pub erupted. As his friends cheered at the screen, Leo felt a different kind of pride. He watched the flawless broadcast\u2014the sharp graphics, the seamless cuts to the roaring crowd\u2014and knew the exact signal path it was traveling. He was an invisible part of this city-wide celebration, a steady hand ensuring the historic moment reached everyone. It was then his ambition crystallized: he didn't just want a job, he wanted to be the master of that signal path.\n\n4.\nIt was last winter, on a drenched morning. The 38 Geary was packed, the windows sweating with condensation. He put his podcast away and just watched the Inner Richmond slide by in the gray light\u2014the neon of a dim sum parlor, a woman huddling under an awning. Instead of the usual commuter annoyance, he felt a profound sense of peace. This route, this bus, this quiet observation\u2014it was his life, and for the first time in a while, it felt completely and utterly whole, just as it was.\n\n5.\nThe final conversation with Maria wasn't a fight, but a quiet, sad admission. Sitting in their Mission apartment, he realized the silence had grown heavier than any words. After she left, he stood looking out the window, not at the life they'd lost, but at the buildings across the street. He understood then that what he truly craved was a foundation. Not a shared dream, but a space that was entirely his own, a quiet harbor in the city he knew so well."
